# compareGraphs
Given axes information such as scaling, this function determines whether a graph drawing matches the provided equation and provides detailed feedback.

The python package [`SymPy`](https://docs.sympy.org/latest/index.html) is used to lambdify the provided equation, and [`PIL`](https://pillow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html) is used to process the PNG URI of the graph drawing.

## Inputs

The structure of the request is as follows:
```json 
{ 
  "response": {
    "student_answer": "<string with PNG URI corresponding to student's drawn graph>",
    "params": {
      "x_upper": "<int>",
      "x_lower": "<int>",
      "y_upper": "<int>",
      "y_lower": "<int>",
      "x_scale": "<int>",
      "y_scale": "<int>",
      "error_bound, optional": "<int>"
    }
  },
  "answer": "<string with correct equation of graph>"
}
```
Please note that no object is passed to the `params` field in the request. Instead, axes information is provided in a different nested object called `params` in the `response`. This was to avoid teachers being required to add this information twice, since they also provide axis information when creating the Graph response area.

In addition, the `answer` must be passed in an expression format that `SymPy`'s [`Lambdify`](https://docs.sympy.org/latest/modules/utilities/lambdify.html#module-sympy.utilities.lambdify) function can parse - i.e. `"-2*x+1"` will be recognised, however `"-2x+1"` will not.


## Outputs
```json
{
  "command": "grade",
  "result": {
    "is_correct": "<bool>",
    "feedback": "<string with detailed feedback>"
  }
}
```

## Examples
Example 1:
```json 
{ 
  "response": {
    "student_answer": "data:image/png;base64,",
    "params": {
      "x_upper": "4",
      "x_lower": "-4",
      "y_upper": "4",
      "y_lower": "-4",
      "x_scale": "1",
      "y_scale": "1"
    }
  },
  "answer": "-2*x+1"
}
```
